<div class="sectionHeading" id="email_confirmation"><strong>I registered for OpenStax Tutor but never received a confirmation email. What should I do?</strong></div>
<ol>
  <li>Check your spam folder for the email and confirm that that OpenStax Tutor is not being blocked by your email provider.</li>
  <li><%= link_to "Click here", new_user_confirmation_path %> and enter the email address you used when creating an account.</li>
  <li>If you don't receive an email within 24 hours, and if your email address is otherwise receiving emails properly, please <%= email_link "support@openstaxtutor.org", "contact us" %>.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  


<div class ="SectionHeading" id="change_section"><strong>I registered for the wrong section. How do I change to a different section?</strong></div
<p>
<p>Go to the class page and check if your registration request is still pending. If so, click Cancel my request to join this class and submit a request to join the correct section.</p>

<p>If you do <strong><em>not</em></strong> see Cancel my request to join this class, email the instructor and ask him/her to switch you to a different section.</p> 

<div class ="SectionHeading" id="multiple_choice"> <strong>I saved a free-form response, so why can't I view the multiple choice answers?</strong></div>

<p>In order to view the multiple choice answers, you must save and <em><strong>lock</strong></em> your free form response. If you save but don't lock your free form answer, you cannot view the multiple choice answers. </p>

<div class ="SectionHeading" id="late"><strong>I finished my assignment late. Can I still get credit if I work the exercises after the due date?</strong></div>

<p><%= SITE_NAME %> automatically withholds credit if you enter answers after the due date. Ultimately, however, it is up to your instructor to provide credit or not.</p>

<div class="SectionHeading" id="fix_work"><strong>I unintentionally saved and locked my free-form and/or multiple choice answers before I was finished! Can I go back and fix my work?</strong></div>

<p>If you selected <em><strong>Save, but don't lock!</strong></em>, you can change your free form answer before locking it in. However, once you have saved and locked your free form, and once you have confirmed your mutlipe choice response, you cannot go back and change your answer. It is up to your professor to give you credit or not.</p>

